Denote by D the center of the trunscribed circle. Let the height of the triangle from the vertex opposite to the base be $x$. Then, from Pythagoras's theorem, we have
\begin{align*}x^2+1^2&=3^2\\
\end{align*}
.\newline
Let $r$ be the radius of the circle. Thus, we have
\begin{align*}r^2-x^2&=\left(\frac{2}{2}\right)^2\\
\end{align*}
Also,
\begin{align*}r+x&=3\end{align*}

